<header class="project-header">
  <h1 class="project-title">Designing the Segment website and marketing message</h1>
  <p class="project-intro">
    The challenge for this project was to make Segment easier to understand
    through the marketing site. We redesigned the site to give visitors a more
    clear idea of what the product does and how it might help them.
  </p>
</header>
<img src="/images/portfolio/segment-site/hero.png" class="work-image">

<div class="text-wrap">
<h3>Understanding the problem</h3>
<ul class="bulleted-list">
  <li>
    <p>
      Most visitors to our marketing site couldn't get a sense of what Segment
      actually is or what the product does.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Oursupport team and Sales team were spending too much time
      answering questions in support tickets and product demos that should've
      been easily answered by our marketing site.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Communicating the value of Segment was getting derailed by technical
      jargon and a bit of graphic clutter.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3>Research</h3>
<p>
  I referenced the <a href="#">Jobs to Be Done</a> research I performed to
  focus the message on exactly what a visitor to the site would needs to know
  about the product:
</p>

<ul class="bulleted-list">
  <li><p>Why someone would care about the product</p></li>
  <li><p>What job they hire the product to do</p></li>
  <li><p>How the product works to help you do that job</p></li>
</ul>

<img src="/images/portfolio/segment-site/jobs.png" style="margin: 2em auto; width: 600px">

<p>
  In Nancy Duarte's <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1nYFpuc2Umk">Tedx Talk</a>
  she describes her research into some of history's most compelling patterns of
  communication. This idea inspired us to structure our story around the
  customer's life before Segment compared to the potential of the customer's
  life after Segment.
</p>
</div>

